article.headline: Oregon State 71, Washington State 62
article.story: CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- Sasa Cuic is staying at Oregon State, and that's very good news for the Beavers. Cuic scored 23 points and Oregon State snapped a six-game losing streak with a 71-62 win over Washington State Thursday night. Cuic, who missed his career-high by one, eclipsed the 20-point mark for the fourth time in six games. It came one day after the sophomore from Rijeka, Croatia, released a statement dispelling rumors that he was leaving to play in Europe at the end of the year. Derrick Low scored 13 points and Chris Henry had a career-high 10 for the Cougars, who fell to Oregon State for the eighth-straight time at Gill Coliseum. Marcel Jones added 12 points and seven rebounds for the Beavers (11-14, 4-10 Pacific-10), who had lost eight of their last nine games since point guard Lamar Hurd went down with a groin injury. Kyle Weaver had 10 points and five rebounds for the Cougars (11-11, 4-9). Low, a sophomore guard from Honolulu, Hawaii, was 6-of-15 from the field and had just one assist, but garnered his highest point total since returning last weekend from a broken foot that had kept him out of eight games. A reserve for most of the season, Cuic has emerged as Oregon State's best scoring threat, entering the game with a 13-point average, best on the team. The 6-foot-10 forward made 6 of 9 shots from the field, including 3 of 4 on 3-pointers. Cuic said he had the Oregon State sports information department put out the statement because he realized his previous comments hadn't been emphatic enough. "I was being asked (about going to Europe) not only by the press, but in class. People were even asking my girlfriend," he said. "I knew I was coming back, and we just decided this was the thing to do." Coming off his first career double-double, senior center Robbie Cowgill had eight points, seven rebounds and six assists for Washington State. The Cougars, who have lost eight of their last 10, were plagued by stretches of cold shooting. Guard Josh Akognon was just 2-of-12 from the field and finished with seven points. Oregon State led 31-21 in the first half, but the Cougars went on a 22-7 run to lead 43-38 by 13:13 in the second half. Oregon State tied the score at 47-all after back-to-back 3-pointers by Cuic and Chris Stephens, then went ahead after Cuic hit another 3 and added two free throws. The Cougars cut the lead to 56-55, but the Beavers went on a 7-0 run with Jones hitting a 3 and Cuic making a pair of free throws and a bank shot from the left side. "They made their shots when it counted and we missed ours," said Cougar coach Dick Bennett. "It came down to that." Low scored with 1:11 left to make it 64-59, but Washington State missed four of its last five field goals, many of them open looks. "It was like somebody put a lid on the hoop," said guard Randy Green. Freshman Brett Casey, Oregon State's third point guard to start in place of Hurd, had career highs with seven points and five assists in 31 minutes for the Beavers. Another point guard, Jason Fontenet, was reinstated for the game after missing a trip to the Arizona schools for disciplinary reasons, but didn't play. Only seven Beavers played, and Oregon State was noticeably worn down by the final minute. But the Beavers made 5 of 10 free throws to keep the game out of reach. "We'd forgotten how it feels to win," Cuic said. "We came into the locker room feeling like we'd won the tournament or something. We were jumping and celebrating." ^
